00:01:09.310 --> 00:01:10.820
across different
units of the class.

00:01:10.820 --> 00:01:13.180
So our model so far,
you'd know on the final

00:01:13.180 --> 00:01:15.700
which unit would be represented
with what proportion.

00:01:15.700 --> 00:01:17.680
You'd optimize your
studying appropriately.

00:01:17.680 --> 00:01:19.450
But of course you
don't know that.

00:01:19.450 --> 00:01:21.097
You face uncertainty
about what will

00:01:21.097 --> 00:01:22.930
be covered in the final
or upper proportion.

00:01:22.930 --> 00:01:24.347
You know the whole
course-- you're

00:01:24.347 --> 00:01:25.798
responsible for the whole class.

00:01:25.798 --> 00:01:27.340
But obviously you
allocate your time.

00:01:27.340 --> 00:01:29.110
You're uncertain
about how to allocate

00:01:29.110 --> 00:01:31.660
your time across the different
subjects on the test.

00:01:31.660 --> 00:01:34.480
So how do you make
that decision?

00:01:34.480 --> 00:01:37.240
We need to bring
our tools to bear

00:01:37.240 --> 00:01:39.910
on thinking about these
kinds of decision making

00:01:39.910 --> 00:01:42.910
under uncertainty situations.

00:01:42.910 --> 00:01:45.040
And this isn't just
about the test.

00:01:45.040 --> 00:01:47.300
I decide whether to
bring my umbrella today.

00:01:47.300 --> 00:01:49.240
If I bring my umbrella, there's
a chance I'm going to lose it.

00:01:49.240 --> 00:01:50.340
But I don't want to get wet.

00:01:50.340 --> 00:01:51.670
I have to think about
whether it's going to rain.

00:01:51.670 --> 00:01:53.170
It all depends on
how certain I am

00:01:53.170 --> 00:01:54.790
it's going to rain, et cetera.

00:01:54.790 --> 00:01:59.785
There's decisions about whether
to bet on a sporting event.

00:01:59.785 --> 00:02:01.160
That's a decision
of uncertainty.

00:02:01.160 --> 00:02:03.010
And that's all the fun
stuff in your life.

00:02:03.010 --> 00:02:05.067
When you get to the
anxiety ridden adult life,

00:02:05.067 --> 00:02:07.150
you've got things like
whether to buy a seven year

00:02:07.150 --> 00:02:10.060
mortgage or a 30 year
mortgage, whether to buy

00:02:10.060 --> 00:02:13.330
health insurance, what
school to put your kids in.

00:02:13.330 --> 00:02:16.780
All these things involve a
huge amount of uncertainty.

00:02:16.780 --> 00:02:20.600
And we have not yet developed
the tools to deal with this.

00:02:20.600 --> 00:02:23.620
What's really cool
is that economics

00:02:23.620 --> 00:02:28.180
has a very useful tool
to think about exactly

00:02:28.180 --> 00:02:29.707
these kinds of situations.

00:02:29.707 --> 00:02:32.290
That much like the other tools
we've dealt with this semester,

00:02:32.290 --> 00:02:34.330
it's pretty easy once
you understand it.

00:02:34.330 --> 00:02:37.900
But it's a huge amount of
power for explaining the world.

00:02:37.900 --> 00:02:40.990
And that's the tool of
expected utility theory.

00:02:46.178 --> 00:02:47.720
And that's what
we'll focus on today.

00:02:47.720 --> 00:02:50.178
That's what we'll learn today,
the tool of expected utility

00:02:50.178 --> 00:02:51.758
theory.

00:02:51.758 --> 00:02:53.300
Now, I'm going to
ask you a question.

00:02:53.300 --> 00:02:55.460
As always, I don't want
you try to outsmart me.

00:02:55.460 --> 00:02:58.152
I just want a
quick, gut reaction.

00:02:58.152 --> 00:02:59.360
I'm going to offer you a bet.

00:02:59.360 --> 00:03:01.115
Not really, but imagine I was.

00:03:01.115 --> 00:03:03.080
I'm going to flip a coin.

00:03:03.080 --> 00:03:05.540
Heads you get $125.

00:03:05.540 --> 00:03:08.070
Tails you give me $100.

00:03:08.070 --> 00:03:09.730
So you win $125
versus lose $100.

00:03:09.730 --> 00:03:10.980
How many of you take that bet?

00:03:13.840 --> 00:03:14.715
So yeah.

00:03:14.715 --> 00:03:16.840
You're a slightly more
aggressive class than usual.

00:03:16.840 --> 00:03:18.310
About 40% of you taking the bet.

00:03:18.310 --> 00:03:20.800
Usually I get more
about 20%, 25%.

00:03:20.800 --> 00:03:21.480
OK.

00:03:21.480 --> 00:03:23.050
Now-- yeah.

00:03:23.050 --> 00:03:24.177
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:03:24.177 --> 00:03:25.010
JONATHAN GRUBER: No.

00:03:25.010 --> 00:03:27.310
It's a one time bet.

00:03:27.310 --> 00:03:30.867
So basically-- now how
do we think about this,

00:03:30.867 --> 00:03:32.200
whether it's a good idea or not?

00:03:32.200 --> 00:03:36.220
Now those who raised your hand
probably quickly did the math

00:03:36.220 --> 00:03:39.880
and did in your head what
we call an expected value

00:03:39.880 --> 00:03:41.300
calculation.

00:03:41.300 --> 00:03:43.600
What's the expected
value of any gamble?

00:03:43.600 --> 00:03:46.840
The expected value of any
gamble is the probability

00:03:46.840 --> 00:03:53.470
that you win times what you win
plus the probability that you

00:03:53.470 --> 00:03:57.070
lose times what you lose.

00:03:57.070 --> 00:03:58.840
So you did that
calculation in your head.

00:03:58.840 --> 00:04:01.750
You said, as long as he's not
cheating, using a fair coin,

00:04:01.750 --> 00:04:11.460
there's a 0.5 times 125
plus 0.5 times minus 100.

00:04:11.460 --> 00:04:17.885
And that is an expected
value of $12.50.

00:04:17.885 --> 00:04:19.760
So those of you who
raised your hand probably

00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:21.700
did that calculation
quickly in your head

00:04:21.700 --> 00:04:24.880
and said, yeah, this is a
positive expected value.

00:04:24.880 --> 00:04:31.440
This is what we call in
economics a more than fair bet.

00:04:31.440 --> 00:04:32.670
More than fair.

00:04:32.670 --> 00:04:36.970
A fair bet is one with
an expected value of 0.

00:04:36.970 --> 00:04:39.910
So a fair bet is one with
an expected value of 0.

00:04:39.910 --> 00:04:41.830
So a bet with a
positive expected value

00:04:41.830 --> 00:04:43.793
is more than fair.

00:04:43.793 --> 00:04:45.710
And you in your head
said, I did that through.

00:04:45.710 --> 00:04:48.950
It's more than fair.

00:04:48.950 --> 00:04:50.960
And that's why some of
you raised your hands.

00:04:50.960 --> 00:04:52.840
But many of you didn't.

00:04:52.840 --> 00:04:54.860
And that doesn't
mean you were wrong.

00:04:54.860 --> 00:04:58.550
It just means this is not the
right way to think about it.

00:04:58.550 --> 00:05:01.040
The right way to think about
it is that what you care about

00:05:01.040 --> 00:05:02.480
is not dollars.

00:05:02.480 --> 00:05:04.870
What you care about is utility.

00:05:04.870 --> 00:05:06.470
Dollars are meaningless.

00:05:06.470 --> 00:05:10.790
What you care about as a
consumer is your utility.

00:05:10.790 --> 00:05:13.610
And so we don't want to
think about expected value.

00:05:13.610 --> 00:05:16.850
We want to think about
expected utility.

00:05:16.850 --> 00:05:18.320
Now, what is expected utility?

00:05:18.320 --> 00:05:22.480
It's the same kind of formula
as this but with one change.

00:05:22.480 --> 00:05:25.510
Expected utility
is the probability

00:05:25.510 --> 00:05:32.240
that you win times your utility
if you win plus the probability

00:05:32.240 --> 00:05:36.780
that you lose times your
utility if you lose.

00:05:39.560 --> 00:05:43.040
And that is somewhat
different than expected value.

00:05:43.040 --> 00:05:46.120
And the reason is
because utility is not

00:05:46.120 --> 00:05:48.290
a linear weighting of dollars.

00:05:48.290 --> 00:05:53.330
Utility is a concave
weighting of dollars.

00:05:53.330 --> 00:05:56.870
As such, because you utility is
a concave weighting of dollars,

00:05:56.870 --> 00:06:01.220
it exhibits diminishing
marginal utility.

00:06:01.220 --> 00:06:03.830
Diminishing marginal
rate of substitution.

00:06:03.830 --> 00:06:05.720
Diminishing marginal
rate of substitution,

00:06:05.720 --> 00:06:08.240
as we talked about ad
nauseam in consumer theory.

00:06:11.330 --> 00:06:15.700
That means that the next
dollar is worth less to you

00:06:15.700 --> 00:06:16.930
than the previous dollar.

00:06:19.500 --> 00:06:21.677
The next dollars worth
diminishing utility.

00:06:21.677 --> 00:06:23.510
The next slice of pizza
is worth less to you

00:06:23.510 --> 00:06:24.930
than the previous
slice of pizza.

00:06:24.930 --> 00:06:27.060
Likewise, the next
dollar's worth less to you

00:06:27.060 --> 00:06:28.950
than the previous dollar.

00:06:28.950 --> 00:06:33.270
As a result, losing
$1 makes you sadder

00:06:33.270 --> 00:06:35.790
than winning $1 makes you happy.

00:06:35.790 --> 00:06:38.190
There's a nonlinearity
that comes

00:06:38.190 --> 00:06:39.810
from diminishing
marginal utility

00:06:39.810 --> 00:06:42.510
and diminishing marginal
rate of substitution.

00:06:42.510 --> 00:06:45.240
So for example, let's think
about our typical utility

00:06:45.240 --> 00:06:47.850
function that we use
previously in consumer theory.

00:06:47.850 --> 00:06:50.302
Utility equals the square
root of consumption.

00:06:50.302 --> 00:06:52.260
And let's just say you
consume all your income,

00:06:52.260 --> 00:06:53.100
as we always did.

00:06:53.100 --> 00:06:55.200
We've talked about savings
the last couple of lectures.

00:06:55.200 --> 00:06:57.120
Let's put savings aside
again and just assume

00:06:57.120 --> 00:06:59.510
people consume all their income.

00:06:59.510 --> 00:07:03.030
And so you utility is the
square root of consumption.

00:07:03.030 --> 00:07:08.760
And let's say you start your
initial consumption, c0 is 100.

00:07:08.760 --> 00:07:13.670
You start with $100
of consumption.

00:07:13.670 --> 00:07:15.270
Your c0 is 100.

00:07:15.270 --> 00:07:18.890
So your initial
utility u0 is 10.

00:07:21.460 --> 00:07:23.430
Now, I give you--

00:07:23.430 --> 00:07:25.020
I offer you this bet.

00:07:25.020 --> 00:07:27.270
What's the expected
utility of this bet?

00:07:27.270 --> 00:07:29.370
Well, the expected
utility of this bet

00:07:29.370 --> 00:07:34.960
is the probability you win,
0.5, times utility if you win,

00:07:34.960 --> 00:07:38.040
where utility if you win is the
square root of your consumption

00:07:38.040 --> 00:07:39.370
if you win.

00:07:39.370 --> 00:07:43.190
What is your
consumption if you win?

00:07:43.190 --> 00:07:46.025
If you win the bet, what
is your consumption?

00:07:46.025 --> 00:07:48.950
Somebody raise your
hand and tell me.

00:07:48.950 --> 00:07:51.540
Starting with 100 and
I made this bet with.

00:07:51.540 --> 00:07:52.150
Yeah.

00:07:52.150 --> 00:07:52.733
AUDIENCE: 225.

00:07:52.733 --> 00:07:54.060
JONATHAN GRUBER: 225.

00:07:54.060 --> 00:07:56.880
You started with
100 and you won 125.

00:07:56.880 --> 00:08:00.520
If you lose the bet,
what do you have?

00:08:04.900 --> 00:08:07.400
What do you have if
you lose the bet?

00:08:07.400 --> 00:08:08.540
0.

00:08:08.540 --> 00:08:09.710
OK?

00:08:09.710 --> 00:08:12.650
So your expected
utility is 0.5 times

00:08:12.650 --> 00:08:14.600
this utility of
what you get if you

00:08:14.600 --> 00:08:19.700
win plus 0.5 times
utility what if you lose.

00:08:19.700 --> 00:08:26.920
Now if you do that math, you
will find that that is 7.5.

00:08:26.920 --> 00:08:28.570
Your expected
utility of this bet

00:08:28.570 --> 00:08:34.429
is 7.5, which is less
than your initial utility.

00:08:34.429 --> 00:08:39.014
So you should not take the bet,
which is through the mechanism

00:08:39.014 --> 00:08:43.010
of psychology why
many of you didn't.

00:08:43.010 --> 00:08:45.650
You should not take the bet.

00:08:45.650 --> 00:08:51.020
And the reason is because
you are what we call risk--

00:08:51.020 --> 00:08:53.570
and humans are what
we call risk averse.

00:08:57.570 --> 00:09:02.660
That risk is inherently
negative value to us.

00:09:02.660 --> 00:09:05.610
A certain dollar is
worth much more to us

00:09:05.610 --> 00:09:07.440
than an uncertain dollar.

00:09:07.440 --> 00:09:10.440
Just like $1 today is worth
more than $1 tomorrow,

00:09:10.440 --> 00:09:14.190
a certain dollar is worth much
more than an uncertain dollar.

00:09:14.190 --> 00:09:17.850
To see why, the best way-- this
intuition here is graphical.

00:09:17.850 --> 00:09:20.910
So let's go to figure 20-1
and just sort of slowly

00:09:20.910 --> 00:09:21.690
walk through this.

00:09:21.690 --> 00:09:23.700
It's a little confusing graph.

00:09:23.700 --> 00:09:26.960
On the x-axis is your wealth,
your total consumption or money

00:09:26.960 --> 00:09:27.460
you have.

00:09:27.460 --> 00:09:28.850
You consume everything you have.

00:09:28.850 --> 00:09:31.650
So it's wealth, or
alternatively consumption.

00:09:31.650 --> 00:09:35.640
On the y-axis of figure
20-1 is your utility.

00:09:35.640 --> 00:09:39.080
It's the graph of how much
you consume against utility.

00:09:39.080 --> 00:09:43.160
And as you can see,
this is a concave graph.

00:09:43.160 --> 00:09:47.660
It's exhibiting diminishing
marginal utility.

00:09:47.660 --> 00:09:52.400
Each dollar of wealth adds
utility but less and less

00:09:52.400 --> 00:09:53.510
over time.

00:09:53.510 --> 00:09:55.730
Just like a slice of
pizza makes you happier

00:09:55.730 --> 00:09:59.040
but less and less over time.

00:09:59.040 --> 00:10:00.000
You get that.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:04.958
So the shape of this curve is
true for any utility function

00:10:04.958 --> 00:10:06.750
that features diminishing
marginal utility.

00:10:06.750 --> 00:10:08.292
That pretty much
any utility function

00:10:08.292 --> 00:10:09.580
we haven't used this semester.

00:10:09.580 --> 00:10:11.700
It's not as if we're
trying to trick you.

00:10:11.700 --> 00:10:13.800
Has diminishing
marginal utility.

00:10:13.800 --> 00:10:17.550
So as a result,
it has this shape.

00:10:17.550 --> 00:10:21.560
Now, with the utility
function of this shape,

00:10:21.560 --> 00:10:25.820
let's evaluate the
gamble I just gave you.

00:10:25.820 --> 00:10:29.610
You start with wealth of 100.

00:10:29.610 --> 00:10:32.920
So you see on the x-axis
the 100 point, that

00:10:32.920 --> 00:10:36.880
corresponds to utility of 10.

00:10:36.880 --> 00:10:40.600
So you can trace up that
100 to utility curve,

00:10:40.600 --> 00:10:42.790
and then you go
over to the y-axis.

00:10:42.790 --> 00:10:45.590
So that corresponds
to a utility of 10.

00:10:45.590 --> 00:10:49.180
Now, think about
what the gamble does.

00:10:49.180 --> 00:10:51.070
What the gamble
does is say look.

00:10:51.070 --> 00:10:54.160
There's two possible outcomes
with 50% chance each.

00:10:54.160 --> 00:10:57.100
One is wealth of 225.

00:10:57.100 --> 00:10:59.560
That is the point all
the way to the right.

00:10:59.560 --> 00:11:02.560
That leaves utility of 15.

00:11:02.560 --> 00:11:04.660
The other's wealth of 0.

00:11:04.660 --> 00:11:06.970
That's the point all
the way to the left.

00:11:06.970 --> 00:11:10.080
That was utility of 0.

00:11:10.080 --> 00:11:11.580
What is the average
of those two?

00:11:11.580 --> 00:11:13.680
Well, it's just a
linear combination.

00:11:13.680 --> 00:11:15.720
So 50% chance of each.

00:11:15.720 --> 00:11:21.770
So the average of those
two is a wealth of 112.5

00:11:21.770 --> 00:11:24.960
but an expected utility of 7.5.

00:11:24.960 --> 00:11:29.210
So you draw a cord between those
two points, between the 0 point

00:11:29.210 --> 00:11:32.810
and point B. You find the
midpoint of that cord.

00:11:32.810 --> 00:11:34.550
That's wealth of 112.5.

00:11:34.550 --> 00:11:37.970
But then you trace that
over to utility function.

00:11:37.970 --> 00:11:43.620
And you see the expected
utility is only 7.5.

00:11:43.620 --> 00:11:47.610
And that's because we're not
using a linear combination.

00:11:47.610 --> 00:11:49.710
We're using a
nonlinear combination--

00:11:49.710 --> 00:11:51.930
a nonlinear concave
combination--

00:11:51.930 --> 00:11:54.960
which means that moving
up in terms of wealth

00:11:54.960 --> 00:11:57.720
makes you less happy than
moving down in terms of wealth

00:11:57.720 --> 00:11:58.740
makes you sad.

00:11:58.740 --> 00:12:01.220
And you're really sad at 0.

00:12:01.220 --> 00:12:03.590
So going for 100
down to 0 makes you

00:12:03.590 --> 00:12:08.683
way sadder than going from 100
up to 225 makes you happier.

00:12:08.683 --> 00:12:10.100
And that's all
because diminishing

00:12:10.100 --> 00:12:12.500
marginal utility of income.

00:12:12.500 --> 00:12:16.720
So it's natural that this gamble
would make you worse off, even

00:12:16.720 --> 00:12:19.950
though it's more than
fair, because, yeah, you're

00:12:19.950 --> 00:12:21.300
somewhat happier if you win.

00:12:21.300 --> 00:12:24.540
If you win, utility
goes up from 10 to 15.

00:12:24.540 --> 00:12:26.000
That's great.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:28.340
But if you lose, utility
goes down from 10 to 0.

00:12:28.340 --> 00:12:30.090
That's really bad.

00:12:30.090 --> 00:12:33.760
So you don't want to
take this risk, which

00:12:33.760 --> 00:12:37.240
is why, although you may
not realize it, many of you

00:12:37.240 --> 00:12:39.880
wouldn't want to
take that gamble.

00:12:39.880 --> 00:12:41.590
So using this
graphic, let's ask--

00:12:41.590 --> 00:12:43.940
are there questions about that?

00:12:43.940 --> 00:12:44.629
Yeah.

