00:24:50.030 --> 00:24:52.750
to your starting point, you
become more and more risk

00:24:52.750 --> 00:24:53.250
neutral.

00:24:56.350 --> 00:24:58.940
Because, yeah, you're a
bit sadder than happier

00:24:58.940 --> 00:25:00.377
but just a bit.

00:25:00.377 --> 00:25:01.460
And remember, it's linear.

00:25:01.460 --> 00:25:07.040
You just take-- so if I did
12 and 1/2 cents versus $0.10,

00:25:07.040 --> 00:25:08.840
then unless you were
crazy risk averse,

00:25:08.840 --> 00:25:11.990
you should take that bet because
essentially you only care--

00:25:11.990 --> 00:25:14.240
at that point it's so tiny
relative to your wealth you

00:25:14.240 --> 00:25:17.750
might as well use
expected value.

00:25:17.750 --> 00:25:21.660
So as gambles become smaller
relative to your income,

00:25:21.660 --> 00:25:26.200
the utility function
becomes locally flatter.

00:25:26.200 --> 00:25:28.780
Utility function
goes locally flatter.

00:25:28.780 --> 00:25:31.780
And as a result, you become
more and more risk neutral.

00:25:35.550 --> 00:25:37.720
Question about that?

00:25:37.720 --> 00:25:38.890
Last point.

00:25:38.890 --> 00:25:42.740
Why did so many of you
still not take that bet?

00:25:42.740 --> 00:25:46.250
Well, the answer is that even
the model we've talked so far

00:25:46.250 --> 00:25:48.727
misses an important
psychological phenomena.

00:25:48.727 --> 00:25:50.810
So now I'm stepping out
of standard microeconomics

00:25:50.810 --> 00:25:52.435
into the realm of
behavioral economics.

00:25:52.435 --> 00:25:54.200
Unfortunately, due to
time this semester,

00:25:54.200 --> 00:25:55.100
I'm not going to
get to my lecture

00:25:55.100 --> 00:25:56.430
on behavioral economics.

00:25:56.430 --> 00:25:57.110
But you guys want to learn--

00:25:57.110 --> 00:25:58.580
I'll talk a little bit about
it in the next few lectures.

00:25:58.580 --> 00:25:59.840
I'll sprinkle it in.

00:25:59.840 --> 00:26:01.940
But course 1113 is
a fascinating course

00:26:01.940 --> 00:26:03.918
we offer here about how
you build psychology

00:26:03.918 --> 00:26:05.210
when you think about economics.

00:26:05.210 --> 00:26:06.830
And here's one example.

00:26:06.830 --> 00:26:09.350
Why is it that even
with this gamble,

00:26:09.350 --> 00:26:11.840
even if I'd done the 12
and 1/2, $0.10 gamble,

00:26:11.840 --> 00:26:13.940
a bunch of you still
wouldn't have taken it.

00:26:13.940 --> 00:26:14.970
Why is that?

00:26:14.970 --> 00:26:18.380
That's because humans not only
feature risk aversion, humans

00:26:18.380 --> 00:26:23.450
also feature loss
aversion, which

00:26:23.450 --> 00:26:26.750
is we have an irrational
behavioral bias

00:26:26.750 --> 00:26:32.580
that losing by itself makes
us sad relative to winning.

00:26:32.580 --> 00:26:35.550
Taking away something
we have makes us sadder

00:26:35.550 --> 00:26:37.710
than getting something new.

00:26:37.710 --> 00:26:39.510
So here's a standard
experiment that's run.

00:26:42.660 --> 00:26:45.150
They get a bunch of $5 mugs.

00:26:45.150 --> 00:26:47.040
Mugs worth about $5.

00:26:47.040 --> 00:26:48.030
They take people.

00:26:48.030 --> 00:26:52.320
And randomly half of the people
they ask, how much would you

00:26:52.320 --> 00:26:54.300
pay for this mug?

00:26:54.300 --> 00:26:56.460
And half the people
they give them the mug

00:26:56.460 --> 00:26:59.490
and say, how much would
you sell your mug for?

00:26:59.490 --> 00:27:01.590
Half people they
say, here's a mug,

00:27:01.590 --> 00:27:02.873
how much would you pay for it?

00:27:02.873 --> 00:27:04.290
Half the people
say, here's a mug.

00:27:04.290 --> 00:27:04.827
It's yours.

00:27:04.827 --> 00:27:05.910
But I want to buy it back.

00:27:05.910 --> 00:27:08.060
How much would you
sell it to me for?

00:27:08.060 --> 00:27:12.350
The average person will pay
$3, but the average person

00:27:12.350 --> 00:27:14.900
wants $7 to sell it back.

00:27:14.900 --> 00:27:16.640
That makes no sense.

00:27:16.640 --> 00:27:18.673
Either way, it's trivial.

00:27:18.673 --> 00:27:19.340
It's just a mug.

00:27:19.340 --> 00:27:21.423
It's trivial relative
to your wealth.

00:27:21.423 --> 00:27:22.090
It's just a mug.

00:27:22.090 --> 00:27:23.530
It doesn't really matter.

00:27:23.530 --> 00:27:26.307
But once people have
it, they feel like, no,

00:27:26.307 --> 00:27:27.140
that's already mine.

00:27:27.140 --> 00:27:28.390
I don't want to sell it.

00:27:28.390 --> 00:27:30.670
That's loss aversion.

00:27:30.670 --> 00:27:35.360
People are biased by
their starting points.

00:27:35.360 --> 00:27:38.470
Your very starting point
dictates your willingness

00:27:38.470 --> 00:27:41.680
to take a gamble,
which is not true

00:27:41.680 --> 00:27:43.390
in a standard economic model.

00:27:43.390 --> 00:27:48.540
But it's true in all laboratory
experiments in psychology.

00:27:48.540 --> 00:27:52.790
So the reason people don't
like gambles are not only

00:27:52.790 --> 00:27:54.360
because they're risk averse.

00:27:54.360 --> 00:27:56.180
But even more,
they're loss averse.

00:27:56.180 --> 00:27:58.880
So for example, there's
great economic studies

00:27:58.880 --> 00:28:04.810
which show that there's a
massive bias against selling

00:28:04.810 --> 00:28:08.180
your house for anything under
the price you paid for it.

00:28:08.180 --> 00:28:09.250
That people sort of--

00:28:09.250 --> 00:28:10.520
they're very sort of
linear, and they're

00:28:10.520 --> 00:28:12.220
willing to sell the house above
the price you paid for it.

00:28:12.220 --> 00:28:14.140
But there's this huge notch
at the price you paid for it.

00:28:14.140 --> 00:28:16.550
They simply don't want to
sell less they paid for it.

00:28:16.550 --> 00:28:18.460
And that's just
loss aversion idea.

00:28:18.460 --> 00:28:20.950
This comes up in
many other contexts.

00:28:20.950 --> 00:28:23.577
So there's two reasons why
people are risk averse,

00:28:23.577 --> 00:28:25.660
that people won't take
gambles-- a standard reason

00:28:25.660 --> 00:28:29.290
and the sort of extra
psychological bias.

00:28:29.290 --> 00:28:33.650
Now, this raises-- this leads
us naturally to the next section

00:28:33.650 --> 00:28:35.320
I want to go to,
which is to talk

00:28:35.320 --> 00:28:41.920
about applications of this
theory and why it's important.

00:28:41.920 --> 00:28:47.190
And the first application I
want to talk about is insurance.

00:28:47.190 --> 00:28:50.710
Insurance is big
business in America.

00:28:50.710 --> 00:28:54.260
Individuals in America
pay individuals--

00:28:54.260 --> 00:28:56.610
forgetting the
government, just people--

00:28:56.610 --> 00:29:01.320
spend $1.5 trillion a year
on insurance products.

00:29:01.320 --> 00:29:03.265
Almost 10% of GDP.

00:29:03.265 --> 00:29:07.140
10% of our entire economy
is people buying insurance.

00:29:07.140 --> 00:29:10.050
Health insurance is the
biggest, life insurance,

00:29:10.050 --> 00:29:14.010
casualty and property insurance,
auto insurance, et cetera.

00:29:14.010 --> 00:29:18.270
Added all up, it's almost a
tenth of our entire economy.

00:29:18.270 --> 00:29:19.780
Why?

00:29:19.780 --> 00:29:22.058
Because they're risk averse,
and also loss averse.

00:29:22.058 --> 00:29:24.100
I'm going to put loss
aversion aside and just use

00:29:24.100 --> 00:29:25.120
the standard framework.

00:29:25.120 --> 00:29:27.040
That just strengthens
the argument.

00:29:27.040 --> 00:29:29.710
But it's because
they're risk averse.

00:29:29.710 --> 00:29:32.530
So let's do the math.

00:29:32.530 --> 00:29:35.505
Imagine you're a single
25-year-old male.

00:29:35.505 --> 00:29:36.880
I'm only being
gender biased here

00:29:36.880 --> 00:29:39.220
because there's no
risk of pregnancy.

00:29:39.220 --> 00:29:42.130
So you're a single 25-year-old
male in perfect health.

00:29:42.130 --> 00:29:46.045
So the only risk you face health
wise is getting hit by a car.

00:29:46.045 --> 00:29:47.170
That's basically your risk.

00:29:47.170 --> 00:29:50.980
Otherwise, you're basically
not going to go to the doctor.

00:29:50.980 --> 00:29:56.770
So essentially, let's say
your income is $40,000.

00:29:56.770 --> 00:29:58.690
That's your income.

00:29:58.690 --> 00:30:01.930
And let's say that there's
a 1%-- since it's Cambridge,

00:30:01.930 --> 00:30:04.870
there's a non-trivial
chance you get hit by a car.

00:30:04.870 --> 00:30:09.940
Let's say there's a 1%
chance, probability 0.01,

00:30:09.940 --> 00:30:13.460
you'll get hit by
a car every year.

00:30:13.460 --> 00:30:19.890
And if you do, you're going to
face $30,000 in medical bills.

00:30:19.890 --> 00:30:22.970
So you have a $40,000 income.

00:30:22.970 --> 00:30:25.370
There's a 1% chance
you get hit by a car.

00:30:25.370 --> 00:30:28.515
And if you do, you'll face
$30,000 in medical bills.

00:30:28.515 --> 00:30:30.890
And let's assume for the minute
you'll still get to work.

00:30:30.890 --> 00:30:32.240
Your income will
always be there.

00:30:32.240 --> 00:30:33.710
You're just going to have to
face a bunch of medical bills.

00:30:33.710 --> 00:30:34.670
There's a separate
issue about whether you

00:30:34.670 --> 00:30:35.870
might have to miss your job.

00:30:35.870 --> 00:30:37.200
That makes this even worse.

00:30:37.200 --> 00:30:38.207
But let's ignore that.

00:30:38.207 --> 00:30:39.290
You get to go to your job.

00:30:39.290 --> 00:30:41.748
You're just going to have to
take a week to get patched up.

00:30:41.748 --> 00:30:45.530
And $30,000 is nothing, by
the way, for a hospital bill.

00:30:45.530 --> 00:30:47.990
A typical, for example,
heart attack hospital bill

00:30:47.990 --> 00:30:49.686
is well over $100,000.

00:30:49.686 --> 00:30:51.500
So $30,000 is pretty modest.

00:30:51.500 --> 00:30:52.376
Yeah.

00:30:52.376 --> 00:30:54.445
AUDIENCE: Wouldn't the
person that hit the guy

00:30:54.445 --> 00:30:56.570
have to get their insurance
cover the medical bill?

00:30:56.570 --> 00:30:58.770
JONATHAN GRUBER: Well, let's
ignore that for a second.

00:30:58.770 --> 00:31:01.070
Right now we're talking about
why you want insurance overall.

00:31:01.070 --> 00:31:02.120
We'll later get into who--

00:31:02.120 --> 00:31:04.240
we can discuss later who
should own that insurance, who

00:31:04.240 --> 00:31:05.115
should bear the risk.

00:31:05.115 --> 00:31:09.440
Right now it's just simply
why you'd want insurance.

00:31:09.440 --> 00:31:14.930
So the expected cost of
getting hit by a car--

00:31:14.930 --> 00:31:18.980
the expected value or expected
cost because it's negative--

00:31:18.980 --> 00:31:21.230
is minus 300.

00:31:21.230 --> 00:31:24.290
So every year you have
a $300 expected cost

00:31:24.290 --> 00:31:26.970
of getting hit by a car.

00:31:26.970 --> 00:31:30.660
And let's say your
utility function is

00:31:30.660 --> 00:31:32.640
u equal square root of c.

00:31:32.640 --> 00:31:34.140
And let's assume
there's no savings.

00:31:34.140 --> 00:31:35.307
You consume all your income.

00:31:38.590 --> 00:31:43.050
How much will this person be
willing to pay for insurance?

00:31:43.050 --> 00:31:46.670
Well, we can solve
that by asking

00:31:46.670 --> 00:31:50.300
at what insurance price
would they be better off

00:31:50.300 --> 00:31:54.080
being insured versus uninsured.

00:31:54.080 --> 00:31:56.740
So let's just do the math.

00:31:56.740 --> 00:32:03.680
If they're uninsured what's
going to happen to them?

00:32:03.680 --> 00:32:05.290
Well, what's their
expected utility?

00:32:05.290 --> 00:32:12.230
Well, there's a 0.1 chance
that they are going to get hit.

00:32:12.230 --> 00:32:17.110
And so their net income will
drop from 40,000 to 10,000

00:32:17.110 --> 00:32:19.340
because they'll have to pay
$30,000 in medical bills.

00:32:19.340 --> 00:32:23.900
So 0.1% chance their
net income be $10,000.

00:32:23.900 --> 00:32:30.010
And there's a 99% chance
that their net income

00:32:30.010 --> 00:32:35.230
will be $40,000.

00:32:35.230 --> 00:32:37.990
That's utility
without insurance.

00:32:37.990 --> 00:32:40.720
Add that up and you get 199.

00:32:40.720 --> 00:32:44.950
So their expected utility
without insurance is 199.

00:32:44.950 --> 00:32:50.662
That's their expected
utility with no insurance.

00:32:50.662 --> 00:32:52.120
Now let's do their
expected utility

00:32:52.120 --> 00:32:53.740
with insurance
but with insurance

00:32:53.740 --> 00:32:55.480
with an uncertain price.

00:32:55.480 --> 00:32:56.710
Let's call the price x.

00:32:59.480 --> 00:33:02.180
What's the utility
with insurance?

00:33:02.180 --> 00:33:09.190
Well, with insurance there's a
0.1% chance that they get hit.

00:33:09.190 --> 00:33:09.930
0.01, I'm sorry.

00:33:09.930 --> 00:33:10.820
It should be an .01.

00:33:10.820 --> 00:33:12.150
My bad.

00:33:12.150 --> 00:33:12.650
Wow.

00:33:12.650 --> 00:33:13.300
I can't believe you
guys missed that.

00:33:13.300 --> 00:33:15.380
You guys are a
little tired today.

00:33:15.380 --> 00:33:18.760
0.01.

00:33:18.760 --> 00:33:22.510
0.01% chance that I get hit.

00:33:22.510 --> 00:33:24.430
Now, if I get hit
with insurance,

00:33:24.430 --> 00:33:26.900
I don't have to pay
my medical bill.

00:33:26.900 --> 00:33:29.790
But I do have to pay
my insurance premium.

00:33:29.790 --> 00:33:35.530
So what I have is I
have $40,000 minus x,

00:33:35.530 --> 00:33:36.780
which is my insurance premium.

00:33:36.780 --> 00:33:38.488
I always have to pay
my insurance premium

00:33:38.488 --> 00:33:40.660
every year, no matter what.

00:33:40.660 --> 00:33:45.697
If I don't get hit,
then I get my 40,000,

00:33:45.697 --> 00:33:47.530
but I also have to pay
my insurance premium.

00:33:50.820 --> 00:33:52.680
So basically these
things are the same.

00:33:52.680 --> 00:33:58.650
So my expected utility is
square root of $40,000 minus x.

00:33:58.650 --> 00:34:02.010
That's my expected utility.

00:34:02.010 --> 00:34:04.280
So how do I solve
for the optimal x?

00:34:04.280 --> 00:34:07.610
Well, I ask at what
x am I better off

00:34:07.610 --> 00:34:09.650
than being uninsured?

00:34:09.650 --> 00:34:13.630
So I set this equal to 199.

00:34:13.630 --> 00:34:16.940
I ask at what x
would I be better off

00:34:16.940 --> 00:34:18.870
than being uninsured?

00:34:18.870 --> 00:34:25.010
And if you solve that, you
get that the x star, the point

00:34:25.010 --> 00:34:27.230
at which you would rather
be insured than uninsured,

00:34:27.230 --> 00:34:32.650
is a premium of $399.

00:34:32.650 --> 00:34:34.889
So you will pay--

00:34:34.889 --> 00:34:39.360
you would rather have
insurance at a cost of 399

00:34:39.360 --> 00:34:42.790
than you would go uninsured.

00:34:42.790 --> 00:34:45.100
Clear on that?

00:34:45.100 --> 00:34:47.440
You'd rather pay
a premium of 399

00:34:47.440 --> 00:34:50.130
than you would go uninsured.

00:34:50.130 --> 00:34:51.659
Now think about what that means.

00:34:51.659 --> 00:34:56.560
Remember, the expected cost of
this accident was only $300.

00:34:56.560 --> 00:35:02.575
That means that you
have a $99 risk premium.

00:35:06.150 --> 00:35:10.430
You are willing to pay $99
to avoid bearing this risk.

00:35:10.430 --> 00:35:11.930
That is what you're
willing to pay--

00:35:11.930 --> 00:35:14.610
before you were willing to
pay me $43.75 to get out

00:35:14.610 --> 00:35:15.600
of that gamble.

00:35:15.600 --> 00:35:17.390
That was your risk premium.

00:35:17.390 --> 00:35:21.540
It's how much you'll pay to
get out of taking a gamble.

00:35:21.540 --> 00:35:24.690
Now before I was
offering a gamble.

00:35:24.690 --> 00:35:25.680
But here's the thing.

00:35:25.680 --> 00:35:28.710
Being uninsured is a gamble.

00:35:28.710 --> 00:35:31.260
Being uninsured is
like taking the gamble.

00:35:31.260 --> 00:35:33.540
So the example I had before,
I locked you in the room.

00:35:33.540 --> 00:35:35.880
And you have to pay me if
you want avoid the bet.

00:35:35.880 --> 00:35:37.353
That's insurance.

00:35:37.353 --> 00:35:38.520
You are locked in this life.

00:35:38.520 --> 00:35:40.590
You're locked into
being in Cambridge.

00:35:40.590 --> 00:35:43.590
You're dealing with a 1% risk
getting hit by a car always.

00:35:43.590 --> 00:35:47.720
So the question is, how much
will you pay to avoid at least

00:35:47.720 --> 00:35:51.090
the financial cost-- forget the
trauma, the financial costs--

00:35:51.090 --> 00:35:53.220
of being hit by that car?

00:35:53.220 --> 00:35:57.090
And the answer is, you'll pay
$99 above the expected damage

00:35:57.090 --> 00:35:59.490
it will do.

00:35:59.490 --> 00:36:03.190
And that is why
insurance is big business

00:36:03.190 --> 00:36:10.100
because people will pay to avoid
being put in risky situations.

00:36:10.100 --> 00:36:12.262
So insurance is a very
profitable exploit.

00:36:12.262 --> 00:36:14.220
Now, in fact, of course,
the insurance industry

00:36:14.220 --> 00:36:15.080
is like any other industry.

00:36:15.080 --> 00:36:17.330
The supply side and
competition, and whether that

00:36:17.330 --> 00:36:19.310
will lead to profits
and stuff like that.

00:36:19.310 --> 00:36:21.080
Depends on the
whole supply side.

00:36:21.080 --> 00:36:22.822
This is just the demand side.

00:36:22.822 --> 00:36:24.280
But the point is
that there's going

00:36:24.280 --> 00:36:26.310
to be huge demand for
insurance, and people

00:36:26.310 --> 00:36:29.330
will be willing to pay much
more than it costs the insurance

00:36:29.330 --> 00:36:29.960
companies.

00:36:29.960 --> 00:36:32.720
The consumers expect
to pay the $300 a year.

00:36:32.720 --> 00:36:35.400
And they're getting almost
$400 a year in premium.

00:36:35.400 --> 00:36:39.290
So the insurance company
makes that money.

00:36:39.290 --> 00:36:42.780
And basically, that's why
insurance is big business.

00:36:42.780 --> 00:36:45.280
Now, here's a couple of things
I'd like you to show yourself

00:36:45.280 --> 00:36:49.160
in your copious spare time.

00:36:49.160 --> 00:36:52.190
First of all, this
risk premium should be

00:36:52.190 --> 00:36:55.900
bigger as the loss gets bigger.

00:36:55.900 --> 00:36:56.400
Why?

00:36:56.400 --> 00:36:58.400
Because you're moving
away from that linear part

00:36:58.400 --> 00:37:01.500
towards the nonlinear part
of the utility function.

00:37:01.500 --> 00:37:03.990
Similarly, this
risk premium should

00:37:03.990 --> 00:37:07.470
fall as your income is higher.

00:37:07.470 --> 00:37:07.970
Why?

00:37:07.970 --> 00:37:09.387
Because once again,
that makes you

00:37:09.387 --> 00:37:11.440
more towards the linear part.

00:37:11.440 --> 00:37:13.780
The bottom line is
the bigger the risk is

00:37:13.780 --> 00:37:17.313
relative to your income, the
more risk averse you become.

00:37:17.313 --> 00:37:19.480
The more you move from that
linear part of the curve

00:37:19.480 --> 00:37:22.330
onto the nonlinear
part of the curve.

00:37:22.330 --> 00:37:24.840
So that's the key thing.

00:37:24.840 --> 00:37:28.520
What matters is risk
relative to your income.

00:37:28.520 --> 00:37:30.920
That's going to determine
your value, your willingness

00:37:30.920 --> 00:37:32.130
to pay for insurance.

00:37:32.130 --> 00:37:35.890
So for example, let's
think of your decision

00:37:35.890 --> 00:37:39.200
to go buy consumer
electronics and the warranty.

00:37:39.200 --> 00:37:41.400
And they always
offer you a warranty.

00:37:41.400 --> 00:37:46.100
Now, those warranties are
expected value negative.

00:37:46.100 --> 00:37:48.680
If you take the
odds of your machine

00:37:48.680 --> 00:37:51.500
breaking-- if you go
to buy a new stereo.

00:37:51.500 --> 00:37:53.360
As if people buy
stereos anymore.

00:37:53.360 --> 00:37:55.940
You're going to
buy a car stereo.

00:37:55.940 --> 00:37:56.945
People still buy those.

00:37:56.945 --> 00:37:59.780
You're going to
buy a car stereo.

00:37:59.780 --> 00:38:02.510
You take the odds of that
breaking times the cost

00:38:02.510 --> 00:38:04.160
it would take to fix it.

00:38:04.160 --> 00:38:06.920
Those multiplied are less
than what they'll charge you

00:38:06.920 --> 00:38:09.260
for the insurance premium.

00:38:09.260 --> 00:38:12.995
It's a bad bet but
it's insurance.

00:38:12.995 --> 00:38:14.870
And so the question is,
should you take that?

00:38:14.870 --> 00:38:18.240
Well, that depends on
how wealthy you are.

00:38:18.240 --> 00:38:22.830
I should never take that because
my car radio cost is tiny

00:38:22.830 --> 00:38:24.610
relative to my income.

00:38:24.610 --> 00:38:26.680
Someone who has low
income might decide

00:38:26.680 --> 00:38:29.030
that's a large gamble
relative my income.

00:38:29.030 --> 00:38:30.140
I don't want to take that.

00:38:30.140 --> 00:38:35.250
So I want to buy the insurance
offered by the manufacturer.

00:38:35.250 --> 00:38:37.950
So once again, it's all
about the size of the risk

00:38:37.950 --> 00:38:39.120
relative to your income.

00:38:39.120 --> 00:38:39.620
Yeah.

00:38:39.620 --> 00:38:41.360
AUDIENCE: What if
I have increased

00:38:41.360 --> 00:38:43.260
chance of breaking my phone?

00:38:43.260 --> 00:38:44.160
JONATHAN GRUBER: Well,
that's a separate issue.

00:38:44.160 --> 00:38:45.327
We'll talk about that later.

00:38:45.327 --> 00:38:47.230
That's called moral hazard.

00:38:47.230 --> 00:38:48.990
You might-- well,
it's not moral hazard.

00:38:48.990 --> 00:38:51.390
What you're saying is
there's heterogeneity.

00:38:51.390 --> 00:38:54.900
And you know you're actually--
that for you it is a fair bet

00:38:54.900 --> 00:38:55.922
because you're clumsy.

00:38:55.922 --> 00:38:57.630
Well, then you should
definitely take it.

00:38:57.630 --> 00:38:58.920
This is saying
risk aversion works

00:38:58.920 --> 00:38:59.690
in favor of you taking it.

00:38:59.690 --> 00:39:01.855
Clumsiness further works
in favor of you taking it.

00:39:01.855 --> 00:39:03.730
And we'll talk about
that in a lecture or two

00:39:03.730 --> 00:39:08.790
when we talk about government
provision of insurance.

00:39:08.790 --> 00:39:10.775
So that's sort of the
first application,

00:39:10.775 --> 00:39:12.150
which is thinking
about insurance

00:39:12.150 --> 00:39:13.900
and why it's such big
business in America.

00:39:13.900 --> 00:39:17.070
And it is huge
business in America.

00:39:17.070 --> 00:39:19.140
The second application
is thinking

00:39:19.140 --> 00:39:21.420
about our friend the lottery.

00:39:21.420 --> 00:39:22.150
Big news lately.

00:39:22.150 --> 00:39:22.650
We talked.

00:39:22.650 --> 00:39:26.003
There was a couple of
huge lottery payouts.

00:39:26.003 --> 00:39:27.920
So let's talk about--
actually, let's do this.

00:39:27.920 --> 00:39:31.430
Let's talk about the lottery.

00:39:31.430 --> 00:39:36.620
Now, the lottery
is a total rip off.

00:39:36.620 --> 00:39:41.103
The expected value of a
lottery purchase is 50%.

00:39:41.103 --> 00:39:43.520
So every dollar you spend on
the lottery, over all lottery

00:39:43.520 --> 00:39:44.450
options--

00:39:44.450 --> 00:39:48.740
for every dollar you spend,
the expected payout is $0.50,

00:39:48.740 --> 00:39:53.000
is a much, much
less than fair bet.

00:39:53.000 --> 00:39:55.010
And yet lotteries
are wildly popular.

00:39:55.010 --> 00:39:57.800
Actually, the beginnings
of this country, the US

00:39:57.800 --> 00:39:58.925
were financed by a lottery.

00:39:58.925 --> 00:40:01.008
Much of the money they
government raised initially

00:40:01.008 --> 00:40:02.840
to set up America
came from a lottery.

00:40:02.840 --> 00:40:05.660
And state lotteries are a huge
source of public financing

00:40:05.660 --> 00:40:08.960
right now across America.

00:40:08.960 --> 00:40:13.790
Now, why do people
play lotteries.

00:40:13.790 --> 00:40:15.920
Well, there's
basically four theories

00:40:15.920 --> 00:40:17.870
for why people play lotteries.

00:40:17.870 --> 00:40:20.330
The first is that
people are risk loving.

00:40:23.980 --> 00:40:26.140
In fact, that were wrong,
people are risk loving.

00:40:26.140 --> 00:40:27.580
That's why they play lotteries.

00:40:27.580 --> 00:40:29.080
How do we know that
theory is wrong?

00:40:31.395 --> 00:40:33.270
How do we know that
theory is its face wrong,

00:40:33.270 --> 00:40:34.437
that people are risk loving?

00:40:36.788 --> 00:40:37.348
Yeah.

00:40:37.348 --> 00:40:38.890
AUDIENCE: The
demonstration in class.

00:40:38.890 --> 00:40:41.353
Lots of didn't
raise their hands.

00:40:41.353 --> 00:40:43.520
JONATHAN GRUBER: Well,
that's one way we might know.

00:40:43.520 --> 00:40:45.320
But how do we know
more globally?

00:40:45.320 --> 00:40:47.180
You guys could just
be a weird bunch.

00:40:47.180 --> 00:40:47.940
How do you we know
more globally?

00:40:47.940 --> 00:40:48.440
Yeah.

00:40:48.440 --> 00:40:49.973
AUDIENCE: Because
of [INAUDIBLE]..

00:40:49.973 --> 00:40:50.890
JONATHAN GRUBER: Yeah.

00:40:50.890 --> 00:40:53.762
But that's absolutely
right, theoretically.

00:40:53.762 --> 00:40:54.720
But that's theoretical.

00:40:54.720 --> 00:40:56.570
In the real world, what
piece of evidence can

00:40:56.570 --> 00:40:57.800
you immediately point
to that I recently

00:40:57.800 --> 00:40:59.780
pointed out that could
show you this is wrong.

00:40:59.780 --> 00:40:59.990
Yeah.

00:40:59.990 --> 00:41:01.190
AUDIENCE: People buy insurance.

00:41:01.190 --> 00:41:02.420
JONATHAN GRUBER:
People buy insurance.

00:41:02.420 --> 00:41:04.610
If they're risk loving, why
are they buying insurance?

00:41:04.610 --> 00:41:06.210
So clearly people
aren't risk loving.

00:41:06.210 --> 00:41:08.230
We wouldn't spend 10%
of GDP on insurance.

00:41:08.230 --> 00:41:10.660
So that theory is clearly wrong.

00:41:10.660 --> 00:41:11.420
OK.

00:41:11.420 --> 00:41:13.150
That's theory one.

00:41:13.150 --> 00:41:16.270
Now, the second theory is
a somewhat subtler version

00:41:16.270 --> 00:41:19.150
of this theory, which
is quite interesting,

00:41:19.150 --> 00:41:23.980
which is that people are both
risk averse and risk loving.

00:41:23.980 --> 00:41:26.920
So that risk aversion varies.

00:41:26.920 --> 00:41:31.870
Risk tolerance, let's
call it, varies.

00:41:31.870 --> 00:41:33.520
And then in
particular, people are

00:41:33.520 --> 00:41:36.760
risk averse over small
gambles, but risk

00:41:36.760 --> 00:41:38.860
loving over big gambles.

00:41:38.860 --> 00:41:41.813
So let's look at figure 20-4.

00:41:41.813 --> 00:41:43.230
This is an example
of what we call

00:41:43.230 --> 00:41:44.703
Friedman-Savage preferences.

00:41:44.703 --> 00:41:45.870
You don't need to know that.

00:41:45.870 --> 00:41:48.480
But they had this idea that
maybe people are locally

00:41:48.480 --> 00:41:51.870
risk averse but
globally risk loving.

00:41:51.870 --> 00:41:53.170
Let's see what this--

00:41:53.170 --> 00:41:55.380
let me explain this.

00:41:55.380 --> 00:41:57.160
This is sort of complicated.

00:41:57.160 --> 00:42:00.420
So imagine that I'm
going to offer you

00:42:00.420 --> 00:42:07.970
a 50-50 gamble
between w1 and w3.

00:42:07.970 --> 00:42:10.850
So a gamble leaves you at w1
and a gamble leaves you at w3

00:42:10.850 --> 00:42:13.460
at 50% chance.

00:42:13.460 --> 00:42:15.650
Well, if we look at
between w1 and w3,

00:42:15.650 --> 00:42:19.020
we're on the concave part
of the utility function.

00:42:19.020 --> 00:42:21.680
And as a result, I will
not take that gamble.

00:42:21.680 --> 00:42:27.470
That gamble leaves me at point
B, which is below B star.

00:42:27.470 --> 00:42:30.020
So basically, I will
not take that gamble.

00:42:30.020 --> 00:42:33.500
That leaves me worse off than
just having w1 plus w3 over 2

00:42:33.500 --> 00:42:34.190
with certainty.

00:42:34.190 --> 00:42:36.050
This is just if you
hold your hand--

00:42:36.050 --> 00:42:38.210
if you hold your hands
between w1 and w3,

00:42:38.210 --> 00:42:40.400
that's just the
graph we saw before.

00:42:40.400 --> 00:42:43.240
You won't take that bet.

00:42:43.240 --> 00:42:45.700
But now let's say
once you get above w3,

00:42:45.700 --> 00:42:49.900
once you're rich enough,
you're risk loving.

00:42:49.900 --> 00:42:52.150
Let's say people are
risk averse at first

00:42:52.150 --> 00:42:53.680
but then get risk loving.

00:42:53.680 --> 00:42:55.240
So if you started it--

00:42:55.240 --> 00:42:59.570
if you said you were starting
at w3 plus w5 over 2,

00:42:59.570 --> 00:43:01.870
I'd offer you a gamble
between w3 and w5.

00:43:01.870 --> 00:43:04.300
Then you're risk
loving in that range.

00:43:04.300 --> 00:43:05.973
And you take it.

00:43:05.973 --> 00:43:08.390
So once you get rich enough,
you start to get risk loving.

00:43:08.390 --> 00:43:10.370
So I talked about before getting
rich or getting more and more

00:43:10.370 --> 00:43:11.662
risk neutral as you get richer.

00:43:11.662 --> 00:43:12.912
What if it goes the other way?

00:43:12.912 --> 00:43:15.410
What if you actually get risk
loving when you get richer?

00:43:15.410 --> 00:43:18.770
Well, then, if you think about
the whole Mega Millions thing,

00:43:18.770 --> 00:43:21.670
you could see that over the
whole distribution from w1

00:43:21.670 --> 00:43:25.110
to w5, people might
want to take that risk.

00:43:25.110 --> 00:43:29.250
That you could actually be
risk loving over these gambles,

00:43:29.250 --> 00:43:30.740
over these giant gambles.

00:43:30.740 --> 00:43:33.630
And that could explain why
people play Mega Millions.

00:43:33.630 --> 00:43:35.130
That over the giant
gambles, they're

00:43:35.130 --> 00:43:38.000
risk loving, even if over
more moderate gambles

00:43:38.000 --> 00:43:39.190
they're risk averse.

00:43:39.190 --> 00:43:41.190
You don't insure yourself
for a billion dollars.

00:43:41.190 --> 00:43:43.180
You insure yourself for
a few thousand dollars.

00:43:43.180 --> 00:43:43.420
Yeah.

00:43:43.420 --> 00:43:45.810
AUDIENCE: How does the size of
the gamble we're talking about

00:43:45.810 --> 00:43:47.768
determine-- we're talking
about small bets that

00:43:47.768 --> 00:43:51.210
are more linear, is it based
on what the player puts in

00:43:51.210 --> 00:43:52.830
or what they get in return?

00:43:52.830 --> 00:43:54.141
JONATHAN GRUBER: Both.

00:43:54.141 --> 00:43:54.820
Both.

00:43:54.820 --> 00:43:57.430
It's basically about--
it's about expected utility

00:43:57.430 --> 00:43:58.373
calculations.

00:43:58.373 --> 00:43:59.790
Yes, it's true,
for Mega Millions,

00:43:59.790 --> 00:44:02.590
you put in $2 for the chance
of winning $1.6 billion.

00:44:02.590 --> 00:44:06.830
But your probability is way,
way lower than 2 in 1.6 billion.

00:44:06.830 --> 00:44:09.510
So it's still unfair.

00:44:09.510 --> 00:44:12.057
So the Friedman-Savage
hypothesis--

00:44:12.057 --> 00:44:13.890
you don't need to know
the name, once again.

00:44:13.890 --> 00:44:15.930
This hypothesis is
that what's happening

00:44:15.930 --> 00:44:20.030
is that people are first risk
averse, but then risk loving.

00:44:20.030 --> 00:44:24.350
Well, how could we test and
actually disprove this theory?

00:44:24.350 --> 00:44:25.032
Yeah.

00:44:25.032 --> 00:44:26.450
AUDIENCE: Like scratch offs.

00:44:26.450 --> 00:44:27.367
JONATHAN GRUBER: Yeah.

00:44:27.367 --> 00:44:29.600
If this is true, people
would love Mega Millions

00:44:29.600 --> 00:44:31.940
but hate $10 scratch offs.

00:44:31.940 --> 00:44:34.400
In fact, the vast majority
of lottery playing

00:44:34.400 --> 00:44:35.690
is not Mega Millions.

00:44:35.690 --> 00:44:37.340
It's $10 scratch off.

00:44:37.340 --> 00:44:40.600
Most money spent on lotteries
are $10 and $20 gambles

00:44:40.600 --> 00:44:43.720
where you bet $1
to win $10 or $20.

00:44:43.720 --> 00:44:46.660
You should be risk averse over
that, or at best risk neutral.

00:44:46.660 --> 00:44:49.480
You shouldn't be risk loving
over those tiny gambles.

00:44:49.480 --> 00:44:52.310
And yet that's most of
what lottery players do.

00:44:52.310 --> 00:44:55.570
AUDIENCE: Wouldn't not
really a scratch off be

00:44:55.570 --> 00:45:00.700
counted internally as not
getting money instead of losing

00:45:00.700 --> 00:45:01.460
money?

00:45:01.460 --> 00:45:01.870
JONATHAN GRUBER:
Well, no, but you've

00:45:01.870 --> 00:45:03.250
lost the dollar you spent.

00:45:03.250 --> 00:45:04.480
And that dollar--

00:45:04.480 --> 00:45:07.380
I still offered you a gamble.

00:45:07.380 --> 00:45:11.310
Spend $1, win $10, with
a 0.05 probability.

00:45:11.310 --> 00:45:13.750
AUDIENCE: I mean, in
the loss averse sense.

00:45:13.750 --> 00:45:14.880
JONATHAN GRUBER: Well, we're
not doing loss aversion.

00:45:14.880 --> 00:45:15.840
Loss aversion is sort of hard.

00:45:15.840 --> 00:45:16.860
You don't have to
think about gambling.

00:45:16.860 --> 00:45:18.240
Loss aversion is
more about losing.

00:45:18.240 --> 00:45:20.310
But in the regular-- you
can see you shouldn't do

00:45:20.310 --> 00:45:21.900
that unless you're risk loving.

00:45:21.900 --> 00:45:24.730
But even this theory would say
you're not locally risk loving.

00:45:24.730 --> 00:45:26.940
So this theory is
out, which leaves us

00:45:26.940 --> 00:45:28.590
with two more theories.

00:45:28.590 --> 00:45:33.920
The first theory is that
this is entertainment.

00:45:33.920 --> 00:45:37.360
That in people's
utility function

00:45:37.360 --> 00:45:39.450
is not just consumption
but the thrill

00:45:39.450 --> 00:45:42.430
of finding out if they won.

00:45:42.430 --> 00:45:43.930
My wife, against
my better judgment,

00:45:43.930 --> 00:45:46.860
went out and bought a
Mega Millions ticket.

00:45:46.860 --> 00:45:49.320
And she got utility
out of waiting

00:45:49.320 --> 00:45:50.807
for that number to come up.

00:45:50.807 --> 00:45:52.140
And it was pretty cheap utility.

00:45:52.140 --> 00:45:54.210
Cost her $2.

00:45:54.210 --> 00:45:57.260
So in that sense, maybe
you play the lottery a lot

00:45:57.260 --> 00:45:59.150
for entertainment.

00:45:59.150 --> 00:46:01.520
That's one theory,
unfortunately,

00:46:01.520 --> 00:46:07.600
the other theory is ignorance.

00:46:07.600 --> 00:46:09.560
That basically, the
saying is the lottery

00:46:09.560 --> 00:46:12.380
is a tax on the stupid.

00:46:12.380 --> 00:46:16.860
Basically just don't understand
what a bad deal this is.

00:46:16.860 --> 00:46:19.440
And the problem is we don't
know which of these theories

00:46:19.440 --> 00:46:20.880
is right.

00:46:20.880 --> 00:46:22.933
And they have very
different implications

00:46:22.933 --> 00:46:23.850
for government policy.

00:46:26.790 --> 00:46:29.950
If this theory is right,
if this theory is right,

00:46:29.950 --> 00:46:32.460
then the government
should support lotteries,

00:46:32.460 --> 00:46:34.470
where essentially the
government is essentially

00:46:34.470 --> 00:46:37.450
getting paid for
providing entertainment.

00:46:37.450 --> 00:46:40.682
It's what the lotteries
often call the voluntary tax.

00:46:40.682 --> 00:46:42.640
That I am basically giving
the government money

00:46:42.640 --> 00:46:43.840
that can run our
schools in return

00:46:43.840 --> 00:46:45.550
for the government giving me the
entertainment value of seeing

00:46:45.550 --> 00:46:46.840
if my scratch off won.

00:46:46.840 --> 00:46:48.100
That's great.

00:46:48.100 --> 00:46:51.080
That's welfare improving.

00:46:51.080 --> 00:46:58.345
Under this theory, we should
be discouraging lotteries.

00:46:58.345 --> 00:47:00.720
That all we're doing is taking
a bunch of ignorant people

00:47:00.720 --> 00:47:03.054
and getting them to
waste their money.

00:47:03.054 --> 00:47:04.445
Yeah.

00:47:04.445 --> 00:47:06.070
AUDIENCE: Is there
almost a possibility

00:47:06.070 --> 00:47:09.300
that there is this concept
of having nothing to lose.

00:47:09.300 --> 00:47:12.650
If you're already too
poor to be able to afford

00:47:12.650 --> 00:47:14.830
your basic needs,
then you might feel

00:47:14.830 --> 00:47:17.270
like, I may as well
try and win the lottery

00:47:17.270 --> 00:47:18.910
and then I would be all set.

00:47:18.910 --> 00:47:19.580
That is--

00:47:19.580 --> 00:47:20.413
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:47:20.413 --> 00:47:23.980
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:47:23.980 --> 00:47:26.060
JONATHAN GRUBER:
That's exactly this.

00:47:26.060 --> 00:47:28.705
That wouldn't explain why
I'd pay the $20 scratch off.

00:47:28.705 --> 00:47:30.080
That's an absolute
reason why I'd

00:47:30.080 --> 00:47:31.455
go ahead, even if
I was starving,

00:47:31.455 --> 00:47:32.730
and play the Mega Millions.

00:47:32.730 --> 00:47:35.120
And that's the Friedman-Savage
hypothesis, absolutely.

00:47:35.120 --> 00:47:38.330
But that can't explain why
in fact, in some low income

00:47:38.330 --> 00:47:40.730
communities, among
some low income groups,

00:47:40.730 --> 00:47:43.070
they'll spend as much
as 20% of their income

00:47:43.070 --> 00:47:47.030
every year on the
lottery, a net.

00:47:47.030 --> 00:47:51.260
They're losing huge amounts of
money on scratch off tickets.

00:47:51.260 --> 00:47:54.140
So the question is, is
that a rational decision

00:47:54.140 --> 00:47:55.910
because they find
it entertaining

00:47:55.910 --> 00:47:57.952
or an irrational decision
because they just don't

00:47:57.952 --> 00:47:59.840
understand what's going on?

00:47:59.840 --> 00:48:02.270
And unfortunately, we
don't know the answer.

00:48:02.270 --> 00:48:05.013
But we do know it's
very important.

00:48:05.013 --> 00:48:06.680
It's important because
there's big bucks

00:48:06.680 --> 00:48:08.720
and in many low
income communities

00:48:08.720 --> 00:48:10.785
it's a huge source
of expenditure.

00:48:10.785 --> 00:48:12.410
So I can't give you
the answer to that.

00:48:12.410 --> 00:48:13.490
I can just tell you it's
an important question.

00:48:13.490 --> 00:48:14.990
I hope someday
someone to figure out

00:48:14.990 --> 00:48:16.657
how to think about
this because it's got

00:48:16.657 --> 00:48:18.060
very important implications.

00:48:18.060 --> 00:48:19.040
So let me stop there.

00:48:19.040 --> 00:48:20.832
That's all I want to
